    <p>For an Indian café serving both espresso and filter coffee, budget for two grinders: one dedicated espresso grinder (on-demand, burr), and one for filter/batch brew. Single-dosing grinders like the EK43 can do both, but workflow suffers at high volume.</p>

    <h2>3. Commercial Refrigeration: Keep It Cold, Keep It Fresh</h2>
    <p>Refrigeration is non-negotiable in a café. Beyond storing ingredients safely, it's also a visual merchandising tool — a well-stocked display chiller showing your cakes, sandwiches, and cold beverages drives impulse purchases and signals freshness to customers.</p>
    <p>Plan for multiple refrigeration units: a display chiller at the front, an under-counter fridge at the coffee bar for milk and fresh syrups, and potentially a reach-in refrigerator in your back-of-house for bulk storage.</p>

    <h3>Display Chillers / Cake Display Counters</h3>
    <p>Display chillers are front-of-house refrigeration units with glass fronts that allow customers to see your food and beverages. They're available in countertop, floor-standing, and curved-glass styles.</p>
