    <h2>9. Water Filtration: The Invisible Foundation of Great Coffee</h2>
    <p>Water quality is one of the most overlooked factors in café setup. Hard water (high in calcium and magnesium) will scale up your espresso machine within months, voiding warranties and causing expensive repairs. Chlorinated water affects coffee flavour. Investing in proper water filtration is non-negotiable — and often a warranty requirement for premium espresso machine brands.</p>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Price Range (INR)</th><th>Use Case</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Under-sink inline filter (basic)</td><td>₹3,000 – ₹8,000</td><td>Basic sediment/chlorine removal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Multi-stage RO system (commercial)</td><td>₹15,000 – ₹40,000</td><td>Hard water areas; blend with RO + unfiltered</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Scale inhibitor filter (cartridge)</td><td>₹8,000 – ₹25,000</td><td>Espresso machine inlet; replace every 6–12 months</td></tr>
        <tr><td>BRITA Purity (German filtration system)</td><td>₹30,000 – ₹60,000</td><td>Specialty coffee; calibrated mineral content</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Water softener (whole-café)</td><td>₹20,000 – ₹80,000</td><td>Commercial kitchen; treats all water supply</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>For most Indian cafés, a combination of a commercial RO system + re-mineralisation filter is the most practical solution. Pure RO water (0 TDS) is also bad for espresso — you need some minerals for proper extraction. The ideal espresso water TDS is 75–150 ppm.</p>

