    <h2>5 Costly Mistakes to Avoid When Buying Café Equipment</h2>

    <h3>1. Buying a Consumer-Grade Espresso Machine</h3>
    <p>Domestic espresso machines (like DeLonghi home units at ₹15,000–₹30,000) are not designed for café use. The pump pressure, boiler capacity, and build quality are insufficient for even 30 cups per day. They'll fail within weeks of commercial use. Always buy commercial-grade machines.</p>

    <h3>2. Under-Investing in Grinders</h3>
    <p>As mentioned earlier — the grinder is half the equation for espresso quality. A ₹3,00,000 espresso machine paired with a ₹15,000 grinder will produce worse espresso than a ₹1,50,000 machine with a ₹70,000 grinder.</p>

    <h3>3. Skipping Water Filtration</h3>
    <p>Hard water destroys espresso machine boilers. A scale buildup that would take years in a household machine takes weeks in a café boiler that runs 8–12 hours daily. Most premium espresso machine warranties in India are void if the machine is used without a water filter. The cost of a descale service (₹8,000–₹15,000) or a boiler replacement (₹40,000+) far exceeds the cost of a good filter.</p>

    <h3>4. Buying Too Much Capacity Too Early</h3>
    <p>It's tempting to buy a 3-group espresso machine when starting out "to be ready for growth." But a 3-group machine costs 2–3x a 1-group machine and uses significantly more electricity and water. Start with what you need now. Upgrade when demand proves it.</p>

    <h3>5. Ignoring After-Sales Service Coverage</h3>
    <p>An espresso machine that breaks down on a Saturday morning with no service technician available until Tuesday is a business catastrophe. Before purchasing any equipment, ask: Who services this in my city? What's the SLA for emergency repairs? Are spare parts readily available in India? The best machine with no local service support is a liability.</p>

