      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How much does it cost to set up a café in India in 2026? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Total café setup cost in India in 2026 ranges from ₹15–₹20 lakh for a small neighbourhood café (15–20 covers) to ₹60–₹1 crore for a premium specialty coffee concept with a full food menu. The equipment budget is typically ₹6–₹50 lakh, with interior fit-out, rental deposit, licences, and working capital making up the rest. A common mid-range café in Tier 1 Indian cities (35–40 covers) typically requires ₹35–₹55 lakh total investment.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the price of a commercial espresso machine in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Commercial espresso machine prices in India range from ₹50,000 for an entry-level single-group machine to ₹5 lakh or more for a premium 2–3 group machine from brands like La Marzocco or Victoria Arduino. For a café doing 80–150 cups per day, a mid-range 2-group machine in the ₹1.5–₹2.5 lakh range (Rancilio Classe, Nuova Simonelli Appia) is the most common and cost-effective choice.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Which espresso machine brand is best for Indian cafés? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For value and reliability, Nuova Simonelli (Italy) and Rancilio (Italy) are the most popular choices in Indian specialty cafés. La Marzocco is the gold standard for premium cafés with the budget. For chain cafés and QSRs prioritising consistency and ease of operation, Schaerer and Franke super-automatic machines are widely used. Avoid unknown Indian-assembled machines unless you've verified the component quality and local service support.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Do I need a glass washer for a small café? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For a café with fewer than 15–20 covers, a commercial glass washer may not be essential — manual washing with a 3-bay sink is manageable. But for 25+ covers, a glass washer will pay for itself within months in labour savings and improved hygiene. At ₹40,000–₹70,000 for an entry-level undercounter unit, it's one of the better ROI investments in café setup. It also ensures proper sanitation (minimum 60°C wash temperature) that manual washing often doesn't achieve consistently.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What POS system should I use for my café in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Petpooja is the most widely used POS for independent cafés and restaurants in India — it's affordable (₹9,999–₹24,999/year), feature-rich, and integrates with Swiggy, Zomato, and major payment gateways. For cafés with a strong delivery focus, UrbanPiper has the best aggregator integration. For a more analytics-heavy operation or chain setup, LightSpeed or Posist offer deeper reporting at higher price points. Avoid free POS systems for a commercial café — they typically have poor support and limited features.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Where can I buy café equipment in India at the best price? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">The best approach is to get quotes from at least 3 suppliers for each category. For espresso machines, go direct to the brand's authorised distributor in your city — this cuts out dealer margins. For refrigeration, Blue Star and Voltas have competitive pricing through their own sales teams. For crockery and glassware, wholesale markets in Delhi (Sadar Bazaar) and Mumbai (Dharavi) offer the lowest prices for basic items. For a comprehensive equipment package with single-point procurement, contact us — we source across categories and negotiate volume pricing from verified suppliers.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What equipment does a café absolutely need on Day 1? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">The non-negotiable Day 1 equipment for a coffee café: (1) commercial espresso machine, (2) quality coffee grinder, (3) commercial blender for cold beverages, (4) under-counter fridge for milk, (5) display chiller for food items, (6) POS system, (7) water filtration, and (8) complete crockery set. Everything else — pass-through dishwashers, batch brewers, waffle makers, outdoor furniture — can be added as revenue grows. Don't delay opening to buy equipment you don't yet need.</div>
